                    (copied from 
            Chaucer, Geoffrey, Canterbury Tales, [Westminster, William Caxton, 1476] ) and
                    Lydgate’s Fall of Princes (1904): see 6799 and 6367. From the Monk’s Prologue, the
                    extract includes VII.1968-90. According to Dixon (1995)
XDixon,  Lori J. 
             “The Canterbury Tales Miscellanies: A Contextual Study of
                Manuscripts Anthologizing Individual Canterbury Tales.” 
         Diss. University of Delaware, 1995, pp. 392-6,
                    the extracts are as follows: Monk’s Tale, VII.1968-2006; Fall of
                        Princes, I.470-966; I.967-1001; I.1380-6; I.1394-1400; I.1338-78;
                    I.1520-33; I.3102-29; I.3788-94; I.3431-58; I.3522-35; I.3795-3801;
                        Monk’s Tale, VII.2015-2374; VII.2399-2766; Fall of
                        Princes, I.1814-41; I.2150-70; I.3102-29; I.3816-43; I.4215-37;
                    I.4240-2; I.4530-43; I.4544-50; I.4551-7; I.5524-30; I.5531-7; I.5538-51;
